s flesh to eat?" (John 6:52), especially to philosophy.We need to question the meaning of "this is my body" in "a way that responds to the needs of our time" (Vatican II). Because of the ways that "Hoc est corpus meum" has shaped our culture and our modernity, this is a problem both for religious belief and for culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aHuman body (Philosophy) 0aHuman bodyxReligious aspectsxCatholic Church. 0aLord's SupperxReal presence. 4aBody. 4aanimality. 4achaos. 4adivinization. 4aeros. 4aeucharist. 4ahumanization. 4aphenomenology. 4aphilosophy of religion. 4atheology. 4atransubstantiation. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Religious.2bisacsh1 aHughes, George08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP eBook-Package 2016z978311071186840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082327043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823270439423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823270439.jpg  a978-3-11-071186-8  NYUP / FUP eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK